# Select numeric columns
numeric_cols = data.select_dtypes(include=['number']).columns

# Dynamically adjust the grid layout
num_features = len(numeric_cols)
rows = math.ceil(num_features / 4)  # Adjust rows dynamically based on the number of features
cols = min(4, num_features)  # Limit columns to 4

# Plot histograms
fig, axes = plt.subplots(rows, cols, figsize=(15, rows * 4))  # Adjust height dynamically
axes = axes.flatten()  # Flatten in case of multiple rows

for i, col in enumerate(numeric_cols):
    sns.histplot(data[col], bins=20, kde=True, ax=axes[i])
    axes[i].set_title(f"Distribution of {col}")

# Remove empty subplots
for i in range(num_features, len(axes)):
    fig.delaxes(axes[i])

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Selected features for deeper analysis
selected_features = [
    "Income", "MntWines", "MntFruits", "MntMeatProducts", "MntFishProducts",
    "MntSweetProducts", "MntGoldProds", "NumWebPurchases", "NumCatalogPurchases",
    "NumStorePurchases", "AcceptedCmpOverall", "Age"
]

# Compute skewness & kurtosis
skew_kurtosis = pd.DataFrame({
    "Feature": selected_features,
    "Skewness": [stats.skew(data[col].dropna()) for col in selected_features],
    "Kurtosis": [stats.kurtosis(data[col].dropna()) for col in selected_features]
})

# Marital status
marital_cols = [col for col in df.columns if col.startswith('marital_')]
if marital_cols:
    marital_data = df[marital_cols].sum().reset_index()
    marital_data.columns = ['Status', 'Count']
    sns.barplot(x='Status', y='Count', data=marital_data)
    plt.title('Marital Status Distribution', fontsize=14)
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.xlabel('Marital Status')
    plt.ylabel('Count')
elif 'Marital_Status' in df.columns:
    marital_counts = df['Marital_Status'].value_counts().reset_index()
    marital_counts.columns = ['Status', 'Count']
    sns.barplot(x='Status', y='Count', data=marital_counts)
    plt.title('Marital Status Distribution', fontsize=14)
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.xlabel('Marital Status')
    plt.ylabel('Count')

# Education level
education_cols = [col for col in df.columns if col.startswith('education_')]
if education_cols:
    education_data = df[education_cols].sum().reset_index()
    education_data.columns = ['Education', 'Count']
    sns.barplot(x='Count', y='Education', data=education_data)
    plt.title('Education Level Distribution', fontsize=14)
    plt.xlabel('Count')
    plt.ylabel('Education Level')
elif 'Education' in df.columns:
    education_counts = df['Education'].value_counts().reset_index()
    education_counts.columns = ['Education', 'Count']
    sns.barplot(x='Count', y='Education', data=education_counts)
    plt.title('Education Level Distribution', fontsize=14)
    plt.xlabel('Count')
    plt.ylabel('Education Level')

# Relationship between income and campaign acceptance

In[33]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_score

# Elbow method and silhouette score
inertia = []
sil_scores = []
k_range = range(2, 11)

for k in k_range:
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=42)
    kmeans.fit(X_scaled)
    inertia.append(kmeans.inertia_)
    sil_scores.append(silhouette_score(X_scaled, kmeans.labels_))

# Plot Elbow Method
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.plot(k_range, inertia, marker='o', color='b', label='Inertia (Elbow Method)')
plt.title('Elbow Method for Optimal k')
plt.xlabel('Number of Clusters')
plt.ylabel('Inertia')
plt.show()

# Plot Silhouette Score
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.plot(k_range, sil_scores, marker='o', color='g', label='Silhouette Score')
plt.title('Silhouette Score for Optimal k')
plt.xlabel('Number of Clusters')
plt.ylabel('Silhouette Score')
plt.show()

def get_marital_status(row):
    if row['marital_Divorced'] == 1:
        return 'Divorced'
    elif row['marital_Married'] == 1:
        return 'Married'
    elif row['marital_Single'] == 1:
        return 'Single'
    elif row['marital_Together'] == 1:
        return 'Together'
    elif row['marital_Widow'] == 1:
        return 'Widow'
    else:
        return 'Unknown'
data['Marital'] = data.apply(get_marital_status, axis=1)

from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_score
silhouette_list = []
for K in range(2,10):
    model = KMeans(n_clusters = K, random_state=7)
    clusters = model.fit_predict(X)
    s_avg = silhouette_score(X, clusters)
    silhouette_list.append(s_avg)

plt.figure(figsize=[7,5])
plt.plot(range(2,10), silhouette_list, color=(54 / 255, 113 / 255, 130 / 255))
plt.title("Silhouette Score vs. Number of Clusters")
